Data and Methods
Our data is from 'data.gov' and is a crime data set that gives crime information from 2020-present given by the Los Angeles Police Department. With this data, we plan to run some 
easy-to-understand models in order to help LAPD. We will use grid-based clustering by dividing LA into geographic cells and predicting crime density in each area. Once we have the 
'hotspot areas', we will add the time variable to this and use change point detection to pinpoint exact months/quarters when crime patterns changed significantly. Then, once we know
the answers (outputs) to our data, we will run a random forest to predict if an area will have high crime given time, location, day of week. If time permits, we also want to run a 
K-Means Clustering model to analyze trends over time and see how the crime clusters have changed from 2020 to 2025.

Data
Our data is from 'data.gov' and is Crime data from 2020-Present in Los Angeles. Here is a link to where to download our data, 'https://catalog.data.gov/dataset/crime-data-from-2020-to-present'. 
Our data has 28 columns, 1,004,991 rows with 13 string columns, 7 integer columns, and 8 float columns. 

The data is reliable because it is from a '.gov' website which means everything they post has to be accurate. According to the Freedom of Information Act, they are legally obligated 
to disclose information—including crime data and records of misconduct—under public records laws.

Our data does have meta data. It is in a json format within the link of the data. Some takeaways from the meta data, published by the Los Angeles Police Department (LAPD), it is
publically available data, and it was last updated on January 2, 2026.


